subject: PLEASE READ: Come Meet PowerPay! (schwag and prizes included)
plain_content: Hey guys, We’re super excited to have PowerPay in our office this Wednesday, March 19th! It will be a great opportunity to ask questions and learn more about our preferred merchant processor J In order to best assist our customers and be available for them, we’re requesting you attend this 30 minute meeting during your lunch hour. What this means: ·         First 30 minutes will be the meeting. Please stay clocked in as you will be getting paid for attending·         Second 30 minutes is your lunch and time to eat. Please remember to clock out as you normally would for lunch·         We will be providing food so you don’t have to worry about going somewhere in 30 minutes J Here are the scheduled times:  Session-9:30am-10amLunch- 10am-10:30amRon TrembulakGreg DurningMatt JohnsonChad OkulovichSabrina McNallyChelsea DellingerSession- 12pm-12:30pmLunch- 12:30pm-1:00pmAaron ErbMichael ErbChris BoyntonHolly SavageBrendan MallonAJ LucisanoDerek StaplesDaniel GreenLeeSession- 12:45pm-1:15pmLunch- 1:15pm-1:45pmApril YounkinAustin OpenshawClay LarsonMegan BoyntonDavid PriceRachel FernandezBlake GhormleyJosh FullmerSession- 2:30pm-3pmLunch- 3pm-3:30pmZach SverdrupAhmad TalebJeremy NoskoJanice NagelBen MoseyAnthony MacDonaldWyatt MackBrianna WaleriusDackota Johnson  We really appreciate your guys’ flexibility and drive to assist our customers! Please let me or your lead know if you have any questions, concerns, or conflicts. Thanks,Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/employees/th-KELLYE%20TURPEN.jpgSmall Business Growth ExpertKELLYE TURPENTechnical Support Lead866-800-0004HYPERLINK "mailto:kellye.turpen@infusionsoft.com"kellye.turpen@infusionsoft.com Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/diver.gifHYPERLINK "http://www.infusionsoft.com/?ls=emailsig"Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/logo.jpgHYPERLINK "http://www.infusionblog.com/"Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/icon-blog.jpg   	 http://www.attendicon.com/   From: Clint Riding Sent: Wednesday, March 12, 2014 10:20 AMTo: psconsultants; customerdelightSubject: Come Meet PowerPay! (schwag and prizes included) Hey Infusionsites! With all your grace and amazingness your presence has been requested on the day of March 19th (Wednesday) to come and meet with the PowerPay team and learn more about who they are as well as what they offer to our customers.  The executive team will be in our office (specifically the theatre) and giving 4 (30 minute) presentations and Q&A to help you to better understand why they are our Preferred Merchant Processor.   We want to be completely sensitive to your schedules and have created the presentation times to fit your schedule.  Your presence is required for one of the sessions (there will be schwag and the first winner of the competition will be announced).  Below are the session times: -          930am-          12pm-          1245pm-          230pm We are looking forward to your attendance and helping our customers succeed! (Please mark on your calendars now!) P.S. Our PowerPay competition that is currently running and I hope you are taking part because each lead that you produce not only helps you but is also a huge help to our customers as well a major part of the revenue that is generated for Infusionsoft. Any questions please let me know.  Thank you!  Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/employees/th-CLINT%20RIDING.jpgSmall Business ChampionCLINT RIDINGStrategic AlliancesPartner Manager 480-499-6861HYPERLINK "mailto:clint.riding@infusionsoft.com"clint.riding@infusionsoft.com Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/diver.gifHYPERLINK "http://www.infusionsoft.com/?ls=emailsig"Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/logo.jpgHYPERLINK "http://www.infusionblog.com/"Description: https://infusionmedia.s3.amazonaws.com/email/signatures/companywide/0210/icon-blog.jpg   There is no way you can't have the best business on this planet. No one stops you but you... that's the only possibility.    - Byron Katie Know anyone who should be using Infusionsoft? HYPERLINK "http://www.infusionsoft.com/refer?empid=Clint%20Riding"Give a Referral!

-->Hey guys, We’re super excited to have PowerPay in our office this Wednesday, March 19th! It will be a great opportunity to ask questions and learn more about our preferred merchant processor J In order to best assist our customers and be available for them, we’re requesting you attend this 30 minute meeting during your lunch hour. What this means: ·         First 30 minutes will be the meeting. Please stay clocked in as you will be getting paid for attending·         Second 30 minutes is your lunch and time to eat. Please remember to clock out as you normally would for lunch·         We will be providing food so you don’t have to worry about going somewhere in 30 minutes J Here are the scheduled times:  Session-9:30am-10amLunch- 10am-10:30amRon TrembulakGreg DurningMatt JohnsonChad OkulovichSabrina McNallyChelsea DellingerSession- 12pm-12:30pmLunch- 12:30pm-1:00pmAaron ErbMichael ErbChris BoyntonHolly SavageBrendan MallonAJ LucisanoDerek StaplesDaniel GreenLeeSession- 12:45pm-1:15pmLunch- 1:15pm-1:45pmApril YounkinAustin OpenshawClay LarsonMegan BoyntonDavid PriceRachel FernandezBlake GhormleyJosh FullmerSession- 2:30pm-3pmLunch- 3pm-3:30pmZach SverdrupAhmad TalebJeremy NoskoJanice NagelBen MoseyAnthony MacDonaldWyatt MackBrianna WaleriusDackota Johnson  We really appreciate your guys’ flexibility and drive to assist our customers! subject: Fwd: My Article on Jinteki

content-type: multipart/alternative; boundary=089e013a140875327104fb889f2f
plain_content:
---------- Forwarded message ----------
From: Brendan Cavalier <brendancavalier@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, Jun 10, 2014 at 9:54 PM
Subject: My Article on Jinteki
To: Jason Flanzer <corpdraw@gmail.com>


Hi Gents,

Below is the article I wrote.  I'd consider it an Op-ed piece, no where near the mathyness of the Stimhack guys, mostly cobbled together from my anecdotal experience, and BS opinions, but I still do feel it's solid.  If the formatting and linking doesn't transfer I'd ask that you please try to at the least keep the links from the first full paragraph, giving credit where it is due.  I'd love your opinions on it, and critique.  I get it if you don't feel its up to snuff, its my first attempt at such a piece, and I feel it could probably still be better.

Thanks,

Brendan



Jinteki: A Disassembly Guide

To sum up the article for the TL:DR group:

1) Don’t loose your cool, i.e. Don’t go snowblind, stay focused

2) Low Click Econ (Daily Casts, Aesop’s, Account Siphon, reoccurring credits)

3) Run every turn (especially against Tennin), but more importantly, remain aggressive, no fear!

4) Run smart, keep track of how many traps you’ve seen, run with your sentry breakers, run with money to spare, keep track of splashes. Run with good situational awareness

5) Run without careless mistakes. Know the cardpool, know the possibilities given Jinteki’s credit pool.

6) Deny Economy. Any way you can, destroy econ assets, Imp Celebrity Gifts, Siphon away.

7) Hit HQ, it’s the stopping point for Snares … but also Agendas.

8) Use cards that allow you to do more in one turn than normally possible: Pro Co, Doppelganger, Security testing, even All-Nighter.

 

To start, credit is due to several people, and if you really want to play against Jinteki, you’ve got to fully understand their motivations and tactics. It took me a LONG time to figure that out, and a lot of that knowledge I garnered from other articles/blogs.  Most notably, Hollis’ ‘My Secret Love Affair with Jinteki’ was eye opening and game changing to me, and several others have really informed my play with Jinteki, especially Sly Squid of Bad Publicity and DB0 with his“Untrashable”.  If this article has any useable tips or knowledge, it is built on their shoulders. I find that I lose quite rarely to Jinteki decks. Maybe because other players haven’t had practice with Jinteki, maybe because they haven’t read Hollis’ blog, but I like to think that it’s because I’ve been playing the other end a lot, and I know what exactly what it takes to disassemble me, thanks to the runners in San Diego. I got to thinking about it, and talked about it on the SanSan South with my friendly arch-nemesis Vincent Perry, listen in for the auditory version.

I’ve been playing Jinteki for a while, and have, in many ways, trained the players in my meta on how to cream me. And they do: repeatedly. After going to the Phoenix Regional, I noticed that I did extraordinarily well with my Corp; far better than I would normally do here, and I realized there may be a need for an article. The Spin Cycle and Honor and Profit have given Jinteki a lot of new and exciting tools, and we’re about to see a lot of powerful new Jinteki players. This article, in reality, is a guide on how to beat me, and the different Jinteki Decks that I’ve had reasonable success with.


To really disassemble Jinteki, you first have to understand the true underlying mechanic, which is different from the other corporations’ in many ways. In short, Jinteki is trying to create several situations throughout the game in which the runner is forced to do more than what  is normally possible in one turn. This may sound similar to what other factions are doing, and it is, but Jinteki’s methodology is quite different. Jinteki does it via heavy ‘work compression’, Jinteki taxes the runner over several turns, doing it more subtly than does Weyland or NBN, and differently from the way HB taxes (though the Bioroids are the closest in style out of the 3).  I won’t go far into that, as Hollis and Sly do a better job than I could. I simply want to explain what it takes to take Jinteki down.

 

So, without further ado here’s my list of how to take apart what soon will be a rising tide of Jinteki.

First, keep your cool, or more precisely; don’t go snowblind.   By ‘don’t go snowblind’ I mean: Don’t let me (Jinteki) confuse you, and throw you off your game.  A good Jinteki player is going to try to redirect away from your plan onto another, Jinteki is especially adept at this through the net damage mechanic, and RP’s forced central run before remote.  Once you get thrown off, and are snowblinded by fear, weird mechanics, and traps, you tend to panic.  Don’t panic.  I’m trying to wear away at you until you need a turn and a half or more to complete what you’d need to do in one turn. Though you need to be more careful with Jinteki, you still need to drive through with whatever your initial game plan was. If it was R&D dig, stick to it (safely), but don’t let yourself get into a position where you don’t know what you’re drawing for. No joke: I have had a post game debriefs in which runners said “at a certain point I didn’t know what I was drawing for”, or “by those last few turns I didn’t even know what to do, draw, run, money up, I just wasn’t sure how or what to attack”. You can’t let yourself get thrown off your game. This is often the biggest advantage Jinteki has against the uninitiated; don’t get scared, don’t panic.  Jinteki is a weird corp, but still a corp, and if your plan was going to mess up Weyland, HB, and NBN, it should work on me.  Just remember your basic strategy and try to stick to it.

 

Second, and this is on a deck building front, you’ll need a ‘low-click’ economy. I’m trying to create situations in which the you need 5, 6, 7 clicks to get past taxing ICE, have drawn enough cards in hand to survive traps, and then also make the runs needed to score agendas. The low click economy helps with this, in that you’re not spending half a turn on a Magnum.  Now Opus is a fantastic economy card normally, but it can actually be a detriment if not used with precision and experience against Jinteki. Cards like Daily Casts, Aesop’s, Account Siphon, Liberated Accounts, Sure Gamble, even Armitage can be a decent way to make a lot of money, fast, as opposed to Magnum, with which you spend your first 5 clicks on it just making up what you spent.  Reoccurring credits, like those from Toolbox, Spinal Modem, Cyber Feeders and Omni-Drives and thestealth chips help tremendously, provided you actually use them. These allow you the clicks needed to draw up, the money to pay past Komainus, and enough cash to pay for the NAPDs and Fetals and install that 3rd critical ICE breaker.  You need to be extremely efficient with the clicks you spend preparing because you’ll need those clicks for all the other ways Jinteki taxes. The all-star of this is, weirdly enough, Professional Contacts, because now every click normally spent drawing up for cards to keep you alive against Snares, Shocks, PE, Hokusai’s, Junebugs ect. is also now gaining you the credits you need.

 

An addendum to the previous point is clickless installation and tutoring. Things like SMC and clone chip are great when you can save the install click for early in the game. Keeping critical cards in hand, vulnerable to net damage, or instead using clicks in a critical turn just to install can be the downfall of a runner.

 

Third: Don’t let fear get the best of you. You gotta run, you gotta make the corp rez ICE, you gotta still run your game plan, you can’t let the fear of net damage totally shatter your plans.  However, don’t get cheeky. Don’t run on Jinteki without a sentry breaker. This is usually only true for other corps once you have a program out, or something you’d like to protect. In the same way you can’t be super aggressive with GRNDL until you’ve got your plascretes out or a ton of money. You don’t want to face-check too much without a lot of money and/or your sentry breakers. You can’t let the fact that Inzanuma exists stop you from running 2 stacked servers … but you gotta do it with respect to the possibility that you might hit something nasty.

Fear is as powerful as an Ash or a Shinobi for generating a scoring window if you let it. You must do it with respect for Komainus and Neural Katanas, but respect and paralysis due to fear are completely different things. But how do I do this? What eliminates fear though? Knowledge. You need to know that with 4 credits, the worst that will happen is a Neural, and keep that in mind. You need to know that with 3 credits, and having an HQ/R&D interface you’re still going to need 3 or maybe 4 in hand to survive a Shock & Fetal AI. With knowledge, not just of the card pool, but of what you’ve seen. What is this player splashing? What is this player’s strategy? How many credits does the corp have? Has the corp held on to or ditched a lot of cards? What could this corp be drawing for? ICE? Traps? Agendas? Intelligence is one of the keys to overcoming a fear inducing opponent, and you need to run, watch, and listen to what’s going on in this game even more carefully against Jinteki.

 

You must deny me money. Without money, I’m not scoring agendas. Without money I’m not advancing traps. Without money, I’m not rezing ICE. This economy denial comes in many flavors. Maybe it’s good old Account Siphon, but a smart corp is going to make you pay for that Account Siphon dearly, most times in a credit taxing HQ or with tag punishment, but in Jinteki that payment is in cards. Make sure you have them in hand. Here’s a specific example:I love my RP deck and with it come Sundews. I’ll protect those Sundews with Chimeras. Once I rez them a couple times the runner will get disheartened (See snowblind) and look for all their breakers, or just ‘let me have it’. This is a mistake. Make me stay broke if you can. You CANNOT let the me generate an overwhelming monetary advantage. If a corp had a Chimera over R&D and that was it, you wouldn’t stop running there would you?  You’d keep running and tax that corp 2 credits every time.  Get an access on R&D or HQ then make me rez that chimera!  Now, If you can’t stop them from generating a ton, you need to generate a ton. You can’t let me do what I call “Yank the money lever”. You can’t let me flatline you to a Shinobi simply because you let myMental Health Clinics run rampant. You cannot just let me have enough money to overcome your whole economy with my Ash’s multiple times. You’ll be having a hard enough time with Caprice for Pete’s sake.

Yes, Sundews and PADs are taxes on the runner. Yeah, I’m going to Interns them back, but eventually, and if you keep your low click economy going, I’ll run out. And buddy, when I run out its bad for me. If I’m clicking for credits, you’ve done your job well. Those are actions not installing ICE, not advancing Agenda’s and traps, not drawing my kill combo, and not getting the runner into impossible situations at game point. Jinteki is going to push you around with net damage, traps, and clicks; don’t let me push you around with money too.

 

As we near the end of the list, we go from general deck building and playstyle to specific tips.

Run HQ. Yes, it is the last stop for Snares, but if you’ve been doing a good job denying me my econ, I’ll go broke setting them off! HQ is also the stop for Agendas, until most Jinteki is ready to score them. Play smart, but be aggressive, and that means on HQ as well. If you watch what happens at high play level game casts when a Jinteki player loses, its not because the runner managed to read the mind of the corp and dodged every trap. Its because when they got hit, the runner took it on the chin, and soldiered on, remaining aggressive, and kept on running, with focus, control, intelligence, and knowledge.

 

The last bit of advice I can give is a reminder: Jinteki is trying to slowly, grindingly, put the runner in a situation where they cannot do in one turn all that must be done in order to stop the corp. Cards that allow you to do exactly that are what will help fight that effect. Oddly enough, most Jinteki:RP players fear a Whizzard Doppelganger deck. When I see this deck I just throw my hands up in disgust. This combo will wreck RP, but what about PE? Or Tennin? If you build a deck to troll RP, when you hit a NBN FA deck you’re hosed. What do you do? Put cards in your deck that allow you to store up clicks when you aren’t being pressured. All-Nighter is a perfect example, though not classically a great it does help you fight work compression. Find cards that allow your deck to do several things with a single click,

 

Certain cards are great against some Jinteki, terrible against others; Wyldeside is a great example of this.  Wyldside is fantastic against PE, but terrible against RP and Tennin.   You’ve got build against the underlying mechanic, not the specific ability.  Playing Net Shield against PE is a pretty decent idea, any other Jinteki player, it will probably not carry its weight.


The only deck that beat me at Regionals was an Andromeda, running Scrubber, Doppelganger and Security Testing. It allowed him to run Archives without fear, gain money, and then wipe out assets cheaply when he did hit them. I would have never thought of that combo, and I’m not sure how he did in the rest of  the tourney, but he tore me up. And I feel he’d tear up PE, as well Tennin. He was also relentless in his intelligent aggression. Always hitting HQ, always trashing my money assets, and trying to get an R&D lock going through Komainu’s .

All in all, I hope this helps you out fighting those Red Corps out there, but I also hope that this article breeds a better form of Jinteki player as well, as your competition will be even fiercer!

 

Good Luck, and run well

Date: Tue, Jun 10, 2014 at 9:54 PMSubject: My Article on JintekiTo: Jason Flanzer <corpdraw@gmail.com>Hi Gents,
Below is the article I wrote.  I'd consider it an Op-ed piece, no where near the mathyness of the Stimhack guys, mostly cobbled together from my anecdotal experience, and BS opinions, but I still do feel it's solid.  If the formatting and linking doesn't transfer I'd ask that you please try to at the least keep the links from the first full paragraph, giving credit where it is due.  I'd love your opinions on it, and critique.  I get it if you don't feel its up to snuff, its my first attempt at such a piece, and I feel it could probably still be better.
Thanks,
Brendan
Jinteki: A Disassembly Guide
To sum up the article for the TL:DR group:
1) Don’t loose your cool, i.e. Don’t go snowblind, stay focused
2) Low Click Econ (Daily Casts, Aesop’s, Account Siphon, reoccurring credits)
3) Run every turn (especially against Tennin), but more importantly, remain aggressive, no fear!
4) Run smart, keep track of how many traps you’ve seen, run with your sentry breakers, run with money to spare, keep track of splashes. Run with good situational awareness
5) Run without careless mistakes. Know the cardpool, know the possibilities given Jinteki’s credit pool.
6) Deny Economy. Any way you can, destroy econ assets, Imp Celebrity Gifts, Siphon away.
7) Hit HQ, it’s the stopping point for Snares … but also Agendas.
8) Use cards that allow you to do more in one turn than normally possible: Pro Co, Doppelganger, Security testing, even All-Nighter.
 To start, credit is due to several people, and if you really want to play against Jinteki, you’ve got to fully understand their motivations and tactics. It took me a LONG time to figure that out, and a lot of that knowledge I garnered from other articles/blogs.  Most notably, Hollis’ ‘My Secret Love Affair with Jinteki’ was eye opening and game changing to me, and several others have really informed my play with Jinteki, especially Sly Squid of Bad Publicity and DB0 with his“Untrashable”.  If this article has any useable tips or knowledge, it is built on their shoulders. I find that I lose quite rarely to Jinteki decks. Maybe because other players haven’t had practice with Jinteki, maybe because they haven’t read Hollis’ blog, but I like to think that it’s because I’ve been playing the other end a lot, and I know what exactly what it takes to disassemble me, thanks to the runners in San Diego. I got to thinking about it, and talked about it on the SanSan South with my friendly arch-nemesis Vincent Perry, listen in for the auditory version.
I’ve been playing Jinteki for a while, and have, in many ways, trained the players in my meta on how to cream me. And they do: repeatedly. After going to the Phoenix Regional, I noticed that I did extraordinarily well with my Corp; far better than I would normally do here, and I realized there may be a need for an article. The Spin Cycle and Honor and Profit have given Jinteki a lot of new and exciting tools, and we’re about to see a lot of powerful new Jinteki players. This article, in reality, is a guide on how to beat me, and the different Jinteki Decks that I’ve had reasonable success with.
To really disassemble Jinteki, you first have to understand the true underlying mechanic, which is different from the other corporations’ in many ways. In short, Jinteki is trying to create several situations throughout the game in which the runner is forced to do more than what  is normally possible in one turn. This may sound similar to what other factions are doing, and it is, but Jinteki’s methodology is quite different. Jinteki does it via heavy ‘work compression’, Jinteki taxes the runner over several turns, doing it more subtly than does Weyland or NBN, and differently from the way HB taxes (though the Bioroids are the closest in style out of the 3).  I won’t go far into that, as Hollis and Sly do a better job than I could. I simply want to explain what it takes to take Jinteki down.
 So, without further ado here’s my list of how to take apart what soon will be a rising tide of Jinteki.
First, keep your cool, or more precisely; don’t go snowblind.   By ‘don’t go snowblind’ I mean: Don’t let me (Jinteki) confuse you, and throw you off your game.  A good Jinteki player is going to try to redirect away from your plan onto another, Jinteki is especially adept at this through the net damage mechanic, and RP’s forced central run before remote.  Once you get thrown off, and are snowblinded by fear, weird mechanics, and traps, you tend to panic.  Don’t panic.  I’m trying to wear away at you until you need a turn and a half or more to complete what you’d need to do in one turn. Though you need to be more careful with Jinteki, you still need to drive through with whatever your initial game plan was. If it was R&D dig, stick to it (safely), but don’t let yourself get into a position where you don’t know what you’re drawing for. No joke: I have had a post game debriefs in which runners said “at a certain point I didn’t know what I was drawing for”, or “by those last few turns I didn’t even know what to do, draw, run, money up, I just wasn’t sure how or what to attack”. You can’t let yourself get thrown off your game. This is often the biggest advantage Jinteki has against the uninitiated; don’t get scared, don’t panic.  Jinteki is a weird corp, but still a corp, and if your plan was going to mess up Weyland, HB, and NBN, it should work on me.  Just remember your basic strategy and try to stick to it.
 Second, and this is on a deck building front, you’ll need a ‘low-click’ economy. I’m trying to create situations in which the you need 5, 6, 7 clicks to get past taxing ICE, have drawn enough cards in hand to survive traps, and then also make the runs needed to score agendas. The low click economy helps with this, in that you’re not spending half a turn on a Magnum.  Now Opus is a fantastic economy card normally, but it can actually be a detriment if not used with precision and experience against Jinteki. Cards like Daily Casts, Aesop’s, Account Siphon, Liberated Accounts, Sure Gamble, even Armitage can be a decent way to make a lot of money, fast, as opposed to Magnum, with which you spend your first 5 clicks on it just making up what you spent.  Reoccurring credits, like those from Toolbox, Spinal Modem, Cyber Feeders and Omni-Drives and thestealth chips help tremendously, provided you actually use them. These allow you the clicks needed to draw up, the money to pay past Komainus, and enough cash to pay for the NAPDs and Fetals and install that 3rd critical ICE breaker.  You need to be extremely efficient with the clicks you spend preparing because you’ll need those clicks for all the other ways Jinteki taxes. The all-star of this is, weirdly enough, Professional Contacts, because now every click normally spent drawing up for cards to keep you alive against Snares, Shocks, PE, Hokusai’s, Junebugs ect. is also now gaining you the credits you need.
 An addendum to the previous point is clickless installation and tutoring. Things like SMC and clone chip are great when you can save the install click for early in the game. Keeping critical cards in hand, vulnerable to net damage, or instead using clicks in a critical turn just to install can be the downfall of a runner.
 Third: Don’t let fear get the best of you. You gotta run, you gotta make the corp rez ICE, you gotta still run your game plan, you can’t let the fear of net damage totally shatter your plans.  However, don’t get cheeky. Don’t run on Jinteki without a sentry breaker. This is usually only true for other corps once you have a program out, or something you’d like to protect. In the same way you can’t be super aggressive with GRNDL until you’ve got your plascretes out or a ton of money. You don’t want to face-check too much without a lot of money and/or your sentry breakers. You can’t let the fact that Inzanuma exists stop you from running 2 stacked servers … but you gotta do it with respect to the possibility that you might hit something nasty.
Fear is as powerful as an Ash or a Shinobi for generating a scoring window if you let it. You must do it with respect for Komainus and Neural Katanas, but respect and paralysis due to fear are completely different things. But how do I do this? What eliminates fear though? Knowledge. You need to know that with 4 credits, the worst that will happen is a Neural, and keep that in mind. You need to know that with 3 credits, and having an HQ/R&D interface you’re still going to need 3 or maybe 4 in hand to survive a Shock & Fetal AI. With knowledge, not just of the card pool, but of what you’ve seen. What is this player splashing? What is this player’s strategy? How many credits does the corp have? Has the corp held on to or ditched a lot of cards? What could this corp be drawing for? ICE? Traps? Agendas? Intelligence is one of the keys to overcoming a fear inducing opponent, and you need to run, watch, and listen to what’s going on in this game even more carefully against Jinteki.

subject: Broadcasts stuck in scheduling fyi
plain_content: Hi Guys, You may still get calls/chats from customers saying a broadcast is stuck in scheduling.  If they created the broadcast prior to last night’s release, then this is the cause.  Have them resend the broadcast and see how it goes.  If it gets hung up in scheduling again, please email the details to Mike Jaramillo Thanks!  Small Business Growth ExpertJanice NagelTech Support480-274-6732HYPERLINK "mailto:janice.nagel@infusionsoft.com"janice.nagel@infusionsoft.com HYPERLINK "http://www.ownyoursummer.com/"oys

plain_content:
---------- Forwarded message ----------
From: Ike Van Atta <j2certified@gmail.com>
Date: Thursday, August 21, 2014
Subject: Good luck
To: Corp Draw <corpdraw@gmail.com>


Brandon,

Congrats on doing well at the tournament. Please extend my congrats to Josh as well. Did you end up spending a ton of money? Did you get the Kros Master game board you wanted?

As a team, we didn't do very well in our pool tournament. Ended up getting knocked out in the 3rd round on the loser's side (2 rounds from being in the money). I shot well, but my team completely fell apart in our very first match (nerves), a match we should have won. Oh well, what can you do! It was our first time in this tournament and there were a ton of great players from all over the United States and Canada.

I won some items in league, awesome, thanks! I am back in town and looking forward to our tournament on Saturday. Sign me up!

I had a couple thoughts/ideas to pass along for possible topics in one of your upcoming pod casts. Maybe you could devote some time to talking about your experience(s) at GenCon:

Here are some questions I would ask you if we were sitting around talking:
  - What were the most popular Ids that you saw/played? Runner vs Corp
    - Any of the newer Ids being played?
  - Did you see any cards from The Lunar Cycle data packs? If so, which ones?
  - Describe your most interesting matches?
  - Best experience / Worst Experience?
  - Knowing what you know now, what changes, if any, would you make in the decks that you played?
  - What challenges did you face that all your prep time didn't prepare you for?
  - What will you do different as you prepare for "Worlds"?

Thanks for listening to me blabber...See you an Saturday!

Ike.

Sent from my iPad

On Aug 19, 2014, at 11:02 PM, Corp Draw <corpdraw@gmail.com> wrote:

Thanks Ike! Hope you are you doing well in your pool tournament. I almost made the top 32 cut in my heat. Josh ended up taking 16th place overall.

I wanted to let you know that I have few items for you from the league. Promos and a box. I'll bring them on Saturday for the tournament if you are back by then. If not, I'll have them for when I see you next. We're planning on making Tuesdays a regular thing. 

Talk to you soon, 


On Fri, Aug 15, 2014 at 1:36 PM, Ike VanAtta <j2certified@gmail.com> wrote:

Good luck in the tournament!

Regards,

Ike Van Atta

Date: Monday, August 25, 2014

Brandon,

I had a couple more thoughts on questions for your Gencon episode:

  - Most Valuable Card (MVC), what did you find was the most valuable card in each of your decks (Corp & Runner)?
  - What was the strongest/most effective "Current" that you played or had played against you (either side)?
  - What was the most unexpected "splashed" card that you saw/played against (either side)?

Krosmaster - Ok, now you've done it...I have made the investment into this game. You have not steered me wrong yet, so I purchased the core set plus 6, character expansion packs. So cool. Trying to get up to speed on the rules / mechanics of the game. Perhaps we could play some tomorrow night at IO? If you're willing to teach a "noob"! 

Ike.

Good questions! I will definitely add them to our Gencon episode. Hoping to record that next week. 

I started a Phoenix Netrunner Group on Facebook. Thought it'd be a good place for locals to find games, chat and find out about tournaments/leagues. If you know anyone else that plays, please invite them to the group. 

https://www.facebook.com/groups/1449372342003077/

plain_content:
---------- Forwarded message ----------
From: Anthony Alonzo <anthonyt.alonzo@gmail.com>
Date: Friday, May 1, 2015
Subject: Episodes for New Players
To: Corp Draw <corpdraw@gmail.com>


I have played many different board games over the years, as well as Magic for the last year, so I typically pick up rules pretty quickly. I even started recording a board game podcast with some friends and have 2 episodes done so far.

I typically listen to your show while I am driving to and from work. When I am listening, you guys will throw out card names pretty quickly, and say something like "yeah, that's a great card" and then reference a specific popular deck or archetype. I have no idea what that card does, nor do I know the popular decks or archetypes yet, and since I am driving, I can't pause and Google things, so I end up pretty lost. I listen to a Magic podcast, and even though the two guys on the show are professional players, whenever they mention a card, they always read off the card text so their listeners know the context. I know that many Netrunner players memorize practically all of the released cards, but until you get there, the listener gets lost really quickly after the 3rd or 4th card referenced. It would be helpful if you described the card whenever you mentioned it, and then explained how the card functions in the deck you are referring to. Something like, "I would definately throw in 3 Sure Gambles into this deck. Sure Gamble is a neutral Event card which costs 5 credits and allows you to gain 9 credits. This Replicating Perfection deck really needs 3 copies because Jinteki struggles with gaining money, and just gets shut down if you are broke (not sure if that's true, just trying to provide an example).

I think the most difficult game mechanics I am still trying to figure out are how ICE works, as well as the turn structure. The chart for when you can or cannot do something isn't as descriptive as it needs to be in the instructions, and a guy that I played against last night seemed to do stuff anytime he wanted. He was razzing things on my turn and his turn, playing events whenever, grabbing money whenever he needed it, activating cards abilities in the middle of my turns. I am sure it was all legit, but was super confusing for me. I am still at the point where I draw a card, move my click token to the first spot on my click track card (yeah I am the only player at this game shop who uses that thing), and then read over all my cards in hand, expose an asset to my opponent and ask if its OK for me to play it on my HQ, lol.

I am hoping that as I continue to study the rulebook, listen to podcasts, and play, I can really pick up this game, and get some of my friends involved. My Reina deck got crushed last night, and I never had what I needed when I needed it, and always had cards I couldn't use in hand, so it's back to the drawing board there. However, my Jinteki personal evolution corp deck functioned amazingly well last night, and I was really pleased with every card I drew into.

On Thursday, April 30, 2015, Corp Draw <corpdraw@gmail.com> wrote:
Hi Tony, 

Thank you for the suggestion, this is definitely something we could probably do. Were there any specific topics, or problems that you are running into that we could talk about? 

Also, if you haven't already, SanSan South is a pretty solid podcast. Their first handful of episodes hit on a lot of beginner topics. You should definitely give them a listen if you haven't.

Talk to you soon! 

On Wed, Apr 29, 2015 at 9:07 AM, Anthony Alonzo <anthonyt.alonzo@gmail.com> wrote:
Hey Corp Draw,

I have recently started playing Android Netrunner about 4 weeks ago.  I went on Board Game Geek and was sent in the direction to obtain 2 core sets, plus the deluxe expansions, and then a handful of the data packs, which I have obtained so far.  I read through the rulebook, and then went to a local shop where I have played 2x so far.

I have listened to 12 episodes so far, however, you guys are way over my head in regards to how the game plays, mechanics, cards, decks, etc...  

Is there a way for you to do a few episodes for new Netrunner players to help ramp them up with understanding the basics of the game, rules, lingo, card abilities, etc? The league organizer at the store I have been playing at basically has every card memorized, and I am sure its going to take me a year to get to that place.  It would be really helpful for listeners like myself who are new to the game if you explained the cards ability as you mention it.

Keep up the shows, and I hope to continue to learn and better understand the game so I can listen to your other episodes in the future and have a better idea of what you guys are exploring.

Thanks,
Tony A.

I even started recording a board game podcast with some friends and have 2 episodes done so far.I typically listen to your show while I am driving to and from work. When I am listening, you guys will throw out card names pretty quickly, and say something like "yeah, that's a great card" and then reference a specific popular deck or archetype. I have no idea what that card does, nor do I know the popular decks or archetypes yet, and since I am driving, I can't pause and Google things, so I end up pretty lost. I listen to a Magic podcast, and even though the two guys on the show are professional players, whenever they mention a card, they always read off the card text so their listeners know the context. I know that many Netrunner players memorize practically all of the released cards, but until you get there, the listener gets lost really quickly after the 3rd or 4th card referenced. It would be helpful if you described the card whenever you mentioned it, and then explained how the card functions in the deck you are referring to. Something like, "I would definately throw in 3 Sure Gambles into this deck. Sure Gamble is a neutral Event card which costs 5 credits and allows you to gain 9 credits. This Replicating Perfection deck really needs 3 copies because Jinteki struggles with gaining money, and just gets shut down if you are broke (not sure if that's true, just trying to provide an example).I think the most difficult game mechanics I am still trying to figure out are how ICE works, as well as the turn structure. The chart for when you can or cannot do something isn't as descriptive as it needs to be in the instructions, and a guy that I played against last night seemed to do stuff anytime he wanted. I think it'd be cool if YOLOP kind-of constantly evolved. I know right now it's catered more toward process-oriented stuff, but I feel that if we have certain technical questions being asked frequently, and they aren't answered in our user guide, then I think they should either be added to the UG, or added to YOLOP, or a technical-oriented YOLOP should be created.
